observations.recommendation:
Immediately send demand letters to officials and employees, who have outstanding cash advance as of December 31, 2023, and to settle the overdue amounts within a specific period. Otherwise, effect the withholding of their salaries pursuant to Section 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 until such time that cash advances are fully settled;

Diligently locate the whereabouts of the two former employees/accountable officer who still have dormant unliquidated cash advance for travel and demand the immediate liquidation of cash advances;

Direct the designated AOs to strictly comply with the rules and regulations particularly on the liquidation of cash advance within the prescribed period to ensure that all disbursements are recorded in the books in the appropriate time/period; and

File a request for authority to write-off dormant or long outstanding unliquidated cash advances, if necessary, to the Office of the Auditor, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

The LCE through the General Services Office shall implement control over the use of government vehicle through properly accomplished and duly approved and serially numbered Driver’s Trip Tickets, a summary of which shall be made at the end of each month in a Monthly Report of Official Travels for audit purposes and strictly adhere with the provisions set forth under COA Circular No. 77-61 dated September 26, 1977 to properly control the utilization of fuel;

Monthly Report on Fuel Consumption and Monthly Report of Official Travels shall likewise be prepared and submitted to the Office of the Auditor for verification purposes to determine the reasonableness of the fuel consumed during the period; and

Strictly comply with Section 4 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 pertaining to the documentary requirements in all government transactions and with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of Republic Act No. 9184 with respect to procedural guidelines in all government procurement.

Exhaust all possible remedies to recover records/documents available to validate claims or else file a request for authority to write-off of dormant receivables accounts to the COA Audit Team Leader in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;

Send demand letters to LGU constituents and employees, Non-Government Organizations (NGOs)/People’s Organization (POs) and National Government Agencies (NGAs) who are recipients of various financial assistance and counterpart funding for the implementation infrastructure project to immediately liquidate or settle the funds granted. Otherwise, cause the refund of the outstanding balances due them; and

Prepare and send demand letter to the contractor representing refund of overpayment amounting to ₱56,924.88.

We recommended and the Management agreed the following:
Municipal Mayor through the MPDC, include in the Annual Investment Program the projects which can readily be implemented by the LGU during the year and prioritize those projects to ensure optimal utilization of the 20% DF;
MPDC (i) coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to conduct a feasibility or preliminary engineering study prior to appropriation of funds to assess the viability of the identified development project/s, enabling more informed decision-making; and (ii) develop feasible and specific solutions to address the identified issues for unimplemented priority projects;
Municipal Engineer to expedite and strictly monitor the implementation of ongoing priority projects while evaluating the performance of contractors involved. In case of unjustifiable delays, compute and hold the erring contractor for any liquidated damages; and
The Local Development Council to: (i) evaluate the necessity of the identified priority PPAs which to date, remained unimplemented, conduct procurement planning to ensure that PPAs are procurement and implementation ready, set specific timeline for completion, and assign personnel responsible to oversee the implementation; and (ii) consider reprogramming/re-aligning the accumulated savings totaling ₱3.171 million to other development projects which should be embodied in the local development plan, and medium-term and annual investment program of the succeeding year.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct:
Municipal Engineer to conduct: (i) monitoring activities through routine inspections of infrastructure development projects from the commencement of implementation, during construction and upon completion thereof in order to avoid recurrence of delayed project delivery to the intended beneficiaries; and (ii) thorough regular and periodic review of the outstanding CIP projects to determine their actual status and physical completion;
BAC Chairperson to coordinate with the concerned contractor to secure final billings and completion documents;
Municipal Accountant to facilitate the immediate reclassification of completed projects to the appropriate PPE account upon receipt of final billing statement, certificate of completion, inspection report, or turnover documents; and
Municipal Accountant compute and impose liquidated damages at least equal to one-tenth of one percent (0.001) of the cost of the unperformed portion for every day of delay which shall be withheld upon final payment without prejudice to other appropriate sanctions that will be imposed by the Management to the erring contractor, if warranted.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the:
Municipal Accountant to reinstate written-off PPEs in the books of accounts until the grant of specific authority by the COA;
General Services Officer to prepare complete documentations required for the filing of request for authority to derecognize non-existing/missing PPEs as required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
LCE to file the request for authority to derecognize non-existing/missing PPEs to the COA Audit Team Leader and/or Supervising Auditor; and
Municipal Accountant, upon receipt of the grant of specific authority by the COA, prepare journal entries to write-off/derecognize from the books the non-existing/missing PPEs.

We recommended and the Management agreed the following:
Limit the practice of serving meals and snacks during meetings particularly those events which are considered among the regular functions or normal activities of the Municipality. Instead, focus the utilization of the government funds for purposes which are more beneficial to the constituents;
Observe economy and austerity measures in the use of government funds which are intended for public purpose;
The Municipal Budget Officer properly charge or limit such expenditures against appropriations for Representation Expenses, Extraordinary and Miscellaneous Expenses, or Discretionary Fund, which are provided for the purpose; and
The Municipal Accountant ensure the completeness of required documents to support the propriety of payments.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to:
Review their respective records (GL and Cashbook) to account for the difference of ₱1.140 million by comparing each other’s entries in their respective records;
Effect the necessary adjustments in their respective records to come up with the accurate Cash-Local Treasury and Cash in Bank account balances;
Henceforth, conduct thorough periodic reconciliation between their respective records so that errors in recording will be corrected/adjusted at the earliest possible time; and
Adhere with the periodic submission of bank reconciliation statements, cashbooks and other financial reports to the Office of the Auditor for review and validation of cash balances, so that errors or deficiencies that may be found in audit could be promptly communicated to the concerned personnel.

The LCE require the coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the designated General Services Officer towards the full implementation of the perpetual inventory method in the recording of all Inventory Accounts to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials; 

The Municipal Accountant and designated General Services Officer maintain the prescribed ledger cards and stock cards, respectively, for each type of Inventory, keep track the actual Supplies Inventory on hand and reconcile the balances of the two inventory records; 

The LCE require the concerned personnel to conduct periodic physical inventory of supplies and materials which shall be reported in the RPCI and submitted to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively; and

Based on the RPCI, the Municipal Accountant compute for the costs of the remaining Inventory using the Moving Average Method, which shall be reconciled with the balance of Inventory accounts in the financial statements.

The LCE through the General Services Office shall implement control over the use of government vehicle through properly accomplished and duly approved and serially numbered Driver’s Trip Tickets, a summary of which shall be made at the end of each month in a Monthly Report of Official Travels for audit purposes and strictly adhere with the provisions set forth under COA Circular No. 77-61 dated September 26, 1977 to properly control the utilization of fuel;

Monthly Report on Fuel Consumption and Monthly Report of Official Travels shall likewise be prepared and submitted to the Office of the Auditor for verification purposes to determine the reasonableness of the fuel consumed during the period; and

Strictly comply with Section 4 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 pertaining to the documentary requirements in all government transactions and with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of Republic Act No. 9184 with respect to procedural guidelines in all government procurement.

Exhaust all possible remedies to recover records/documents available to validate claims or else file a request for authority to write-off of dormant receivables accounts to the COA Audit Team Leader in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;

Send demand letters to LGU constituents and employees, Non-Government Organizations (NGOs)/People’s Organization (POs) and National Government Agencies (NGAs) who are recipients of various financial assistance and counterpart funding for the implementation infrastructure project to immediately liquidate or settle the funds granted. Otherwise, cause the refund of the outstanding balances due them; and

Prepare and send demand letter to the contractor representing refund of overpayment amounting to ₱56,924.88.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
The Inventory Committee, headed by the Designated GSO, to undertake the completion of physical inventory for those PPE accounts not subjected to physical count aggregating ₱3.901 million, and continue the practice of conducting the annual inventory-taking to establish the physical existence of the PPE accounts, and to monitor/determine the assets’ whereabouts, custodianship and conditions.
The Municipal Accountant trace/locate the related documents of the unidentified properties to substantiate the recorded PPE balances of ₱9.219 million and thereafter, maintain the corresponding PPELC and RPLC;
The Designated GSO maintain the required Property Cards per category of PPE. Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs) should also be issued for all newly acquired PPE including those counted during the physical inventory;
Regularly reconcile balances between the PC and PPELC to establish the completeness and accuracy of the reported PPE accounts; and
Human Resource consider the designation of a full time GSO who will handle the functions relative to property monitoring, reporting and the like instead of being handled by the Municipal Treasurer in concurrent capacity.

We recommended the Management to direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer of the following:
Exert extra efforts to collect the loan receivables by sending demand letters to LGU constituents, employees, and cooperatives who are recipients of loan assistance, to immediately settle the loan balances due from them;
Loan receivables from LGU officials and employees, whether holding permanent positions or under the contract of service, be immediately collected, otherwise, these should be deducted from their salaries, taking into consideration the minimum take-home pay under existing rules and regulations;
Outstanding loan balances of the two cooperatives should be collected without delay after issuing demand letters to their respective management;
Retrieve all the documents pertaining to the loan such as promissory notes to determine the names of the co-makers and consider imposing applicable sanctions to these co-makers in the event the loan beneficiaries will not be able to pay their long outstanding obligations with the LGU; and
If found to be no longer collectible, the Head of the Agency consider the filing of request for authority to write-off the accounts following the guidelines and procedures outlined in Commission on Audit (COA) Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Immediately send demand letters to officials and employees, who have outstanding cash advance as of December 31, 2023, and to settle the overdue amounts within a specific period. Otherwise, effect the withholding of their salaries pursuant to Section 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 until such time that cash advances are fully settled;
Diligently locate the whereabouts of the two former employees/accountable officer who still have dormant unliquidated cash advance for travel and demand the immediate liquidation of cash advances;
Direct the designated AOs to strictly comply with the rules and regulations particularly on the liquidation of cash advance within the prescribed period to ensure that all disbursements are recorded in the books in the appropriate time/period; and
File a request for authority to write-off dormant or long outstanding unliquidated cash advances, if necessary, to the Office of the Auditor, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to:
Review their respective records (GL and Cashbook) to account for the difference of ₱21,914.69 by comparing each other’s entries in their respective records;
Effect the necessary adjustments in their respective records to come up with the accurate Cash-Local Treasury account balance;
Henceforth, conduct thorough periodic reconciliation between their respective records so that errors in recording will be corrected/adjusted at the earliest possible time; and
Adhere with the periodic submission of accounts and financial reports to the Office of the Auditor so that errors or deficiencies that may be found in audit could be early communicated to the concerned personnel.

We recommended the Management and agreed to following courses of action:
The Bids and Awards Committee and the Municipal Engineer properly plan and schedule all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave the way for their timely implementation and completion;
Management implement immediately all the projects under the continuing appropriations, otherwise, unimplemented PPAs which are no longer feasible should be considered for immediate realignment subject to budgetary rules or reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the 20% Development Fund for reprogram/re-appropriation to other development projects;
The Local Development Council (LDC) evaluate the necessity of the identified priority PPAs which to date, remained unimplemented, conduct procurement planning to ensure that PPAs are procurement and implementation ready, set specific timeline for completion, and assign personnel responsible to oversee the implementation; and
Management reprogram/re-align the accumulated savings totaling ₱0.874 million to other development projects which should be embodied in the local development plan, and medium-term and annual investment program of the succeeding year.

Management ensure optimum utilization of the calamity fund for expenditures that address the key objectives of disaster risk reduction and management as envisioned under R.A. No. 10121;

The Sangguniang Bayan pass a resolution authorizing the Municipal Treasurer to open a separate depository account for the unexpended LDRRMF accruing to the special trust fund for ease of monitoring of receipts, transfers and utilization thereof; 

The Municipal Treasurer facilitate the transfer of unexpended LDRRM fund balance from the General Fund to the STF depository account; and

The Municipal Accountant record the transfer of the unexpended balance of the QRF and DRRMF-MOOE for the current and previous years within the five-year validity period to the STF using the “Trust Liability-DRRMF” account in the Trust Fund books.

The GSO prepare the required RIS and RSMI for all issued relief goods, supplies and materials which should be submitted to the Accounting Unit for the recording of appropriate expense;

The requisitioning department prepare and submit: (i) the list of beneficiaries indicating the quantity and specifics of items distributed and the signature of recipients signifying their acceptance/acknowledgement of the relief/welfare goods; and (ii) photographs taken during distribution of said items to the beneficiaries; and

The Municipal Accountant: (i) record the expense only upon receipt of RIS and RRSI from the GSO and other supporting documents; and (ii) ensure that the release and use of the QRF be supported with Local Sanggunian Resolution and the declaration of the state of calamity.

Stop the practice of charging expenditures against the 20% Development Fund for non-development programs and projects as enumerated under Section 3.2.5 of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1 dated November 4, 2020; 

Strictly utilize the 20% DF only for those priority programs and projects intended for the attainment of desirable socio-economic targets and outcomes of the LGU;

Revert to the 20% DF the total amount of ₱1.821 million representing disbursements for non-development projects, which shall be re-appropriated to finance only those development programs, projects and activities allowable to be charged against said Fund; and

Submit justification why the incurrence of expenses for T-shirts with print and supplies and food expense amounting to ₱51,831.00 and ₱87,664.00, respectively should not be disallowed in audit, otherwise, refund the total amount which are considered unnecessary expenditures.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following courses of actions:
The Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical inventory of all PPE items, prepare the required RPCPPE and a copy thereof shall be submitted to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of the following year;
Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC) and Property Cards for each group of PPEs shall be maintained by the Accounting Office and General Services Office, respectively and reconciliation between these two records shall be undertaken regularly;
Subsidiary ledgers for each type of PPE shall be maintained by the Accounting Office which should be in agreement with the balances of the controlling accounts in the GL;
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entries to set up the correct depreciation reckoned from the date of acquisition/completion of the assets up to the present by debiting prior period adjustment and crediting accumulated depreciation and ensure monthly recognition of depreciation expense of all depreciable PPE accounts;
The Municipal Engineer furnish the Municipal Accountant with the Project Status Report for partially completed or on-going projects as of year-end indicating their percentage of completion and cost incurred to date, which shall be the basis of the latter in recording the Construction in Progress account to ensure complete, accurate and timely recognition of assets in the financial statements; and
The Municipal Accountant make the necessary adjustments in the books to correct all erroneous recording/classifications noted by debiting appropriate PPE accounts and crediting prior period adjustments.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Local Chief Executive (LCE) require the contractor to fast track the completion of the projects to avoid possible rescindment of contracts as stipulated in Section 68 of Republic Act (RA) No. 9184;
The Municipal Engineer intensify the monitoring activities through routine inspections of infrastructure development projects from the commencement of implementation, during construction and upon completion thereof in order to avoid recurrence of delayed project delivery to the intended beneficiaries;
The Municipal Accountant compute and impose liquidated damages at least equal to one-tenth of one percent (0.001) of the cost of the unperformed portion for every day of delay which shall be withheld upon final payment without prejudice to other appropriate sanctions that will be imposed by the Management to the erring contractor;
Management provide the Engineering Office with adequate manpower and equipage so that supervision and monitoring activities over implemented projects can be properly and regularly undertaken; and
The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) carefully evaluate the prospective bidder’s technical, legal and financial capabilities taking into consideration the history and experience of the Municipality with the contractor relative to project undertakings, so that contracts for infrastructure development projects are awarded only to contractors that are reliable to accomplish the projects on time.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Analyze, review, reconcile and monitor all booked receivables and adjust accordingly to ensure that only valid receivables are recorded in the books;
Analyze all the Receivables that are dormant, long outstanding and unsubstantiated for proper disposition and recognition;
Exhaust all possible remedies to recover records/documents available to validate claims or else file a request for authority to write-off of dormant receivables accounts to the COA Audit Team Leader in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;
Reclassify the accounts which were improperly recorded as Accounts Receivable to their proper accounts;
Maintain subsidiary ledgers and supporting documents to substantiate the recorded balance of Receivable accounts;
Send demand letters to LGU constituents and employees, Non-Government Organizations (NGOs)/People’s Organization (POs) and National Government Agencies (NGAs) who are recipients of various financial assistance and counterpart funding for the implementation infrastructure project to immediately liquidate or settle the funds granted. Otherwise, cause the refund of the outstanding balances due them; and
Prepare and send demand letter to the contractor representing refund of overpayment amounting to ₱56,924.88.

We recommended and Management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to:
Investigate the beginning balance of the Due to NGAs account to determine its nature, specific purpose and the source agency from which the funds were received. Thereafter, facilitate evaluation to determine whether the corresponding projects have been implemented and return the unused funds to the source agency, if warranted;
Analyze, review, reconcile and monitor all booked Due to NGAs account and adjust accordingly to ensure that only valid entries to the account are recorded in the books;
Reclassify the accounts which were improperly recorded as Due to NGAs to their proper accounts;
Maintain subsidiary ledgers and supporting documents to substantiate the recorded balance of Due to NGAs account and monitor the availability of funds to avoid incurrence of negative balance to the account;
Copies of Memorandum of Agreement and supporting documents be furnished to the Audit Team for review and evaluation of the terms and conditions; and
Unutilized funds no longer needed after completion of the specific programs and projects should be returned to the source agency pursuant to Item 4.9 of COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
At the beginning of the year, the Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant of a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year;
The Municipal Accountant use the Real Property Tax Account Register/ Taxpayer’s index card, Certified List of Taxpayers and Tax due and demandable submitted by the Municipal Treasurer as basis for setting up the RPT/SET receivables and deferred credits at the start of the year;
The Municipal Accountant maintain subsidiary ledgers for RPT/SET Receivables and Deferred Credits to facilitate easy reconciliation and monitoring of the balances; and
The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant conduct reconciliation of records to establish a realistic balance of RPT and SET Receivables. Appropriate adjustments shall be made in the books for any discrepancies found thereto.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Ensure that only necessary expenditures are incurred, observe prudence and fiscal restraint in utilizing government funds which are intended for public purpose;
Expenses for catering services incurred during meetings and conferences where participants thereto are all LGU personnel in the performance of their regular duties/functions should not be charged to government funds;
Submit justification why the incurrence of the foregoing expenses should not be disallowed in audit, otherwise, refund the total amount which are considered unnecessary expenditures; and
Constantly be guided by COA Circular No. 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012 and strictly adhere thereto to avoid incurrence of irregular, unnecessary, excessive, extravagant and unconscionable expenditures.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary adjustments to recognize a liability representing the unutilized balance of the BGCM fund amounting to ₱819.56 and inappropriate charges amounting to ₱25,085.80 or a total of ₱25,905.36 and maintain a separate subsidiary ledger in compliance with LBC No. 125 dated April 7, 2020;
Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant and Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to submit the required documents to the Office of the Auditor for further evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 dated April 6, 2020;
Replenish the amount of ₱25,085.80 representing inappropriate charges against the BGCM fund which shall form part of the unutilized balance for re-appropriation to other allowable PPAs for COVID-19 response, otherwise, the remaining balance, if any, shall be reverted to the National Treasury after the lifting of the State of Calamity;
Ensure that only authorized COVID-19 related PPAs shall be charged against the BGCM fund as enumerated under DBM Local Budget Circular No. 125 dated April 7, 2020; and
Require the BAC to strictly comply with the posting requirement of GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 dated April 6, 2020 for information purposes and to promote transparency and accountability in the conduct of Emergency Procurement under the Bayanihan Act.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Require the concerned accountable officers to settle their cash advances pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002, especially at year-end, for the timely recognition of expenses in the books of accounts;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to officers and employees unless the previous cash advance is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made;
The OIC-Municipal Accountant monitor the liquidation of cash advances by sending demand letters regularly and withhold the payment of any money due them in case of their failure to settle the liquidation of cash advances despite demand;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to conduct thorough review and evaluation of the affected dormant accounts and comply with all the documentary requirements and procedures under COA Circular 2016-005 for the proper disposition such as request for write-off and the disclosure of dormant accounts; and
The OIC-Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and accountable officers ensure completeness of documents and payroll bear complete signatures of payees and proper approval before disbursements/ liquidations are made;

We recommended that:

The Municipal Mayor direct the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of the physical inventory of the Municipality’s PPE and submit to the Audit Team the properly accomplished RPCPPE;

The RPCPPE shall be reconciled with the accounting records in order to ensure that the PPE account balances are fairly presented in the financial statements. The discrepancies should be investigated and necessary adjustments should be made to come up with a complete and accurate balance of asset accounts, PPE in the financial statements;

The Accounting Office should religiously maintain the PPELC to provide a detailed information of the PPE which can be of great importance in the conduct of the physical inventory;

The Municipal Treasurer as Property Custodian of the Municipality maintain Property Cards and provide/attach property sticker to each PPE item for ease of reference and property tagging;

Management give considerable time and additional personnel to work on the reconciliation of the of the physical count with the accounting records and the subsequent inventory tagging of all PPE and assignment of property codes for a more facilitative identification and tracking of the location of the properties.  Inventory Tag should be attached to the newly acquired equipment before these are distributed to the intended end-users;

A Municipal Valuation Committee be created to determine the appraised value of donated properties and those properties found on station during the inventory taking so that these properties can be correctly recorded in the books of accounts of the municipality;

Management consider the creation of a General Services Office (GSO) who will handle the receipt, issuance and recording of the procured and issued supplies and property; and

Henceforth, inventory taking and reconciliation of related subsidiary records should be regularly undertaken and regarded with utmost importance.

We recommended that Management: 

Require the Municipal Accountant to compute the correct depreciation expenses of its assets and a journal entry must be drawn to update/correct the accumulated depreciation by a debit to depreciation expense (for the current year depreciation), debit to prior year’s adjustment (for the prior year’s depreciation) and a credit to accumulated depreciation (for the total unrecorded depreciation);

Exert effort through the General Services Office/Office of the Municipal Treasurer, to reconstruct and update its property records and reconcile with the accounting records to facilitate the setting up and periodic provision of depreciation for those depreciable assets not provided with depreciation;

Create an appraisal committee to conduct evaluation of assets whose records could not be found in order to establish the commencement of depreciation of the subjected assets and determine their depreciable cost and estimated remaining life for the computation of their respective depreciation; and

Henceforth, the Municipal Accountant see to it that all depreciable properties owned by the LGU are provided with depreciation in accordance with the above-mentioned rules and regulations to ensure its fair presentation in the financial statements.

We recommended that:

The Municipal Assessor furnish the Municipal Treasurer on or before the 31st day of December of each year, an assessment roll containing a list of  all real property, whether taxable or exempt, located within the territorial jurisdiction of the Municipal Government of Lezo, Aklan and  a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties;

The Municipal Treasurer prepare a duly certified list showing the name of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant to serve as the basis in setting up the beginning balance of RPT/SET Receivable in the books of accounts.  In such manner, the related receivable account and deferred liability will be presented fairly in the financial statements;

The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant conduct reconciliation of records to establish a realistic balance of receivables for the RPT Taxes and SET Taxes so that necessary adjustment(s) in the books of accounts can be effected for a more realistic presentation of the balances in the financial statements;

The Municipal Treasurer religiously update the individual Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR) or Taxpayer’s Index Card every time a payment is received from the taxpayer which shall serve as the basis in the preparation of the List of Delinquent Real Property Taxpayers as of the end of the year, the total of which shall equal the RPT/SET Receivable at year end;

The Local Chief Executive (LCE), Municipal Treasurer and other concerned Municipal Officials exert concerted efforts to intensify collections of long outstanding RPT and SET Receivables including the interest thereon so that more development programs may be implemented for the benefit of the constituents; and

The Municipal Accountant maintain subsidiary ledgers for RPT and SET Receivables to facilitate smooth reconciliation of balances.

We recommended that the OIC-Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer:

Exercise prudence and due diligence in the processing of transactions;

Require the accountable officers to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period;

Ensure that no cash advances are granted unless the previous ones are liquidated;

Ensure completeness of documents and payroll bear complete signatures of payees and proper approval before disbursements/ liquidations are made;

Monitor the liquidation of cash advances by sending demand letters regularly and withhold the payment of any money due them in case of their failure to settle the liquidation of cash advances despite demand;

Conduct thorough review and evaluation of the affected dormant accounts and comply with all the documentary requirements and procedures under COA Circular 2016-005 for the proper disposition such as request for write-off and the disclosure of dormant accounts; and

See to it that all applicable laws, rules and regulations affecting cash advances and disbursement of funds are strictly adhered to.

We recommended the following:

The Sangguniang Bayan immediately pass a resolution authorizing the Municipal Treasurer to open a separate depository account for the 20% Development Fund and each special account for the operations of the public market and the public cemetery;

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to immediately transfer the amount of ₱13.696 million to the 20% Development Fund depository account;

The OIC-Municipal Accountant be required to maintain Special Accounts in the General Fund and prepare the financial reports with necessary supporting schedules for each economic enterprises and development projects. Separate financial statements for the economic enterprises and development projects shall likewise be prepared at year-end to form part of the schedule of the General Fund Trial Balance as mandated under Section 313 of R.A. 7160 and Section 110 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1; and

Henceforth, require the Municipal Treasurer to transfer monthly the amount equivalent to 20% of the IRA to the 20% Development Fund depository account for easy monitoring of the fund and to safeguard it for possible misuse.

We recommended that Management:

Open a separate depository account for Special Trust Fund to deposit the transfer of the Agency’s unutilized QRF and DRRMF-MOOE of the previous years, receipts from NDRRMF, DRRMF from other LGUs and other sources;

Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate and the Municipal Treasurer to immediately transfer the amount of ₱2.512 million to the Special Trust Fund account;

Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to use the account, Trust Liabilities-DRRMF in the Trust Fund books to record transfers of the LGU’s unutilized QRF and DRRMF-MOOE of the previous years, receipts from NDRRMF, DRRMF from other LGUs and other sources as provided in Section 5.1.12 of COA Circular no. 2012-002; and 

Henceforth, require the Municipal Accountant Designate and the Municipal Treasurer to effect the immediate cash transfer at the end of the year, the LGU’s unutilized QRF and DRRMF-MOOE of the current year to the Special Trust Fund account.

